{
  "doc_id": "14123",
  "text": "The nuclear cofactor DOR (Diabetes-and Obesity-Regulated gene, also known as Tp53inp2 or C20orf110), is a key regulator of autophagy [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Originally identified as a protein highly expressed in muscle, heart and brain, DOR localizes in nuclear bodies in proliferating cells [CITATION_3] . In agreement with its nuclear localization, DOR functions as an enhancer of the transcriptional activity of the thyroid hormone receptor TRa1, and DOR loss-offunction reduces thyroid hormone function in muscle cells [CITATION_4] . This function is driven mainly by the N-terminal part of the protein, whereas the C-terminal fragment of DOR exhibits inhibitory activity [CITATION_5] . Moreover, DOR physically interacts with TRa1 and T 3 -responsive promoters, as assessed by co-immunoprecipitation and ChIP assays [CITATION_6] . The Drosophila homolog of DOR, dDOR, is a coactivator of the ecdysone receptor [CITATION_7] . dDOR binds the ecdysone receptor and is required for its maximal transcriptional activity. In the absence of dDOR, flies display a number of ecdysone loss-of-function phenotypes such as impaired spiracle eversion, impaired salivary gland degradation, and pupal lethality [CITATION_8] .",
